===Etymology 1===
{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|うめ}}

{{IPAchar|/me<sub>2</sub>/}} → {{IPAchar|*/mme<sub>2</sub>/}} → {{IPAchar|/mume<sub>2</sub>/}} → {{IPAchar|/ume<sub>2</sub>/}} → {{IPAchar|/ume/}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=うめ|-}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref><ref name="DJS">{{R:Daijisen}}</ref>  Found already in the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}'' with the ''ume'' reading, completed some time after 759 CE.<ref>{{RQ:Manyoshu|5|822}}, text [http://jti.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/manyoshu/Man5Yos.html#822 here]</ref>

Probably ultimately from {{der|ja|ltc|sort=うめ|-}} {{ltc-l|梅}},<ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref><ref name="DJS">{{R:Daijisen}}</ref> with the borrowed {{IPAchar|/me/}} reading gaining a pronounced kind of initial {{IPAchar|/m/}} sound, perhaps realized as {{IPAchar|/mme/}}.  The phonetic spelling was often rendered as {{ja-l|むめ}} ({{IPAchar|/mme/}} or {{IPAchar|/mume/}}) from the {{w|Heian period}},<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJS">{{R:Daijisen}}</ref> with ''mme / mume'' and ''ume'' apparently existing in free variation.  The reading eventually settled on {{ja-l|うめ}} ({{IPAchar|/ume/}}).  Compare the similar pattern of phonetic shift for {{m|ja|馬|tr=ma → *mma → muma → uma||horse}}, from {{cog|ltc|-}} {{ltc-l|馬}}.

